e the home islands could imagine their nation's imperial reach. George Behlmer argues that Britain's early visitors to the Pacific-mainly cartographers and missionaries-wielded the notion of savagery to justify their own interests. But savage talk was not simply a way to objectify and marginalize native populations: it would later serve also to emphasize the fragility of indigenous cultures. Behlmer by turns considers cannibalism, headhunting, missionary activity, the labor trade, and Westerners' preoccupation with the perceived "primitiveness" of indigenous cultures, arguing that British representations of savagery were not merely straightforward expressions of colonial power, but also belied home-grown fears of social disorder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aPrimitive societieszMelanesia. 4aMelanesia. 4aPacific Ocean. 4aWilliam Rivers. 4acannibalism. 4acolonialism. 4aheadhunting. 4amissionaries. 4asavagery. 7aHISTORY / Oceania.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360595440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605954423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605954.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles